 flourish in Graeco-Roman society. Hadrian's reign was the starting point of that process and opened new possibilities of self-definition and external self-presentation to Christianity, as well as to other social and religious agencies. Differently from Judaism, however, Christianity fully seized the opportunity, thus gaining an increasing place in Graeco-Roman society, which ultimately led to the first Christian peace under the Severan emperors. The point at issue is examined from a multi-disciplinary perspective (including archaeology, cultural, religious, and political history) to challenge well-established, but no longer satisfactory, historical and hermeneutical paradigms. The contributors aim to examine institutional issues and sociocultural processes in their different aspects, as they were made possible on Hadrian's initiative and resulted in the merge of early Christianity into the Roman Empire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aChristianity and other religionsxJudaismxHistoryyEarly church, ca. 30-600. 0aChurch historyyPrimitive and early church, ca. 30-600. 0aJudaismxRelationsxChristianityxHistoryyTalmudic period, 10-425. 4aChristentum im Römischen Reich. 4aChristentum und Judentum. 4aFrühes Christentum. 4aHadrian. 4aHadrians Religionspolitik. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Rome.2bisacsh  aChristianity and Judaism.  aChristianity and Roman Empire.  aEarly Christianity.  aHadrian's Religious Policy.  aHadrian, Roman Emperor.1 aBazzana, Giovanni Battista, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalandra, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 